In this project I look at three different incident categories from the Baltimore crime database: Armed Person, Destruction of Property, and Cutting Aggravated Assault incidents. I display each category on its own map, represented with circles that are colored by time of day of the arrest. The coloring procedure simply represents the incidents as lighter shades the closer they are to noon, with arrests occurring at midnight displayed in black. Clicking on a circle on the map displays the exact time of the arrest as a popup.

import folium
import requests
import pandas

arrest_table = pandas.read_csv("http://www.hcbravo.org/IntroDataSci/misc/BPD_Arrests.csv")

arrest_table = arrest_table[pandas.notnull(arrest_table["Location 1"])]

arrest_table["lat"], arrest_table["long"] = arrest_table["Location 1"].str.split(",").str
arrest_table["lat"] = arrest_table["lat"].str.replace("(", "").astype(float)
arrest_table["long"] = arrest_table["long"].str.replace(")", "").astype(float)

from datetime import datetime

map_1 = folium.Map(location=[39.29, -76.61], zoom_start=11)

# get only the rows which represent an armed person incident
# (index 7 holds the first instance of an armed person in the original table)
armed = arrest_table['incidentOffense'] == arrest_table.iloc[7]['incidentOffense']
armed_table = arrest_table[armed]

for i in range(0,len(armed_table)):
    # Read in the time as a datetime object
    t = datetime.strptime(armed_table.iloc[i]['arrestTime'], '%H:%M:%S')
    # Transform the timestamp value to be some value between 0 and 255, where
    # noon becomes 255 and midnight becomes 0. 1:00am and 11:00pm are the same
    # distance from midnight, so they are transformed to the same value.
    c = 255-abs(((t.timestamp()+2208945600.0)))*255/43200.0
    
    folium.Circle(
        radius=50,
        location=[armed_table.iloc[i]['lat'], armed_table.iloc[i]['long']],
        popup=armed_table.iloc[i]['arrestTime'],
        
        
        color='RGB('+ str(0) +','+ str(c) +','+ str(c) +')',

        fill= True,
    ).add_to(map_1)
    
map_1

  • Many daytime arrests (light blue circles)
  • Rather concentrated within the central city area

Conclusions

These maps show that certain destruction of property incidents are more likely to see arrests at night, while armed person arrests occur more during the day. They also indicate locations that are hotspots for some categories: the Patterson Park and Brooklyn Park areas both appear to host a significant number of cutting and destruction of property incidents.

It's not wise to make too many direct comparisons among the three graphs because they represent different numbers of data points. However there is one trend that stands out: dark points tend to be clustered, while light-colored points do not seem to have many geographical patterns. There are more likely to be crime (or arrest) hotspots at night, but during the daytime their locations are less predictable.

Using this analysis, officers could change patrolling patterns to focus on different areas during different times of day. Citizens could use it when choosing where to avoid during certain times of day, when to be most alert about personal security, or where to purchase property -- starting a business at a destruction of property hotspot is a risky investment.
